  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Baton Rouge Area Flood Recovery</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Assist at least 15 families with other unmet needs arising from the flooding, such as temporary housing, income replacement, replacement of material household goods, and purchasing additional storage as needed., Assist at least 20 flood survivor families with housing repair and remediation., As needed, purchase home building and repair materials for homeowner-supervised home rebuilds for those affected by flooding., Recruit and utilize at least 50 volunteers, both local and out-of-state teams, for housing repair and remediation., As needed, care for and feed volunteer teams, including providing appropriate housing, feeding, physical materials, volunteer safety, volunteer training and supervision of teams., Utilize food bank ministries at Trinity Episcopal Church, Baton Rouge, to meet increased need from the floods for at least 50 families., Engage parishes in advocacy work on behalf of individuals declined benefits., As appropriate, establish congregation engagement programs for possible future response and funding., As needed, provide pastoral and spiritual care for those affected by the flooding.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Individuals</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Diocese of Louisiana is responding after severe flooding in August 2016 destroyed tens of thousands of homes. The Diocese is working in 11 parishes (counties) across Louisiana to help the most vulnerable survivors recover from the flood and supporting volunteer teams (from both Louisiana and from other states) as they work on rebuilding projects.</narrative>
  </description>
